.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/leanne-matlach.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(200,4,'2015-08-19 21:16:55','2015-08-20 01:16:55','Kerry Nagle is the COO of Straighterline, a unique low cost online education platform that provides direct to consumer for-credit courses. In her role, Kerry is responsible for managing the company’s day-to-day operations, including technology, product, marketing, sales and customer support, as well as fully owning the execution of company strategy.\r\n\r\nKnown for her incredible work ethic and team-oriented approach, Kerry specializes in building high performing teams, collaborating across C-level suites and designing company infrastructures to ensure scalability and efficient performance. Prior to Straighterline, Kerry spent more than 10 years in the digital advertising space including companies such as Advertising.com and Millennial Media (NYSE: MM).\r\n\r\nAs Millennial Media’s 14th employee, Kerry established daily business operations, policies, protocols, and procedures that directly contributed to the company’s growth from less than 15 employees and $5M in revenue, to 600 employees worldwide, $341.8M in annual revenue and a successful public offering.\r\n\r\nKerry held several different executive roles at Millennial Media, with the most recent being Senior Vice President of International Corporate Development. In this position, Kerry built the company’s presence in Europe, Asia Pacific and Latin America, further enhancing the depth of her operational knowledge across cultures and economies.\r\n\r\nWith experience on both the buy and sell side of acquisitions, Kerry also led comprehensive due diligence efforts at Millennial Media, as well as the successful integration of a $200M competitive stock acquisition.\r\n\r\nKerry has also been a member of various advertising and mobile groups such as the MMA and IAB, and was a contributing author of Mobile Marketing for Dummies.','Kerry Nagle','','publish','closed','closed','','kerry-nagle','','','2015-08-20 13:09:51','2015-08-20 17:09:51','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=200',0,'speaker','',0),(202,3,'2015-08-19 21:28:40','2015-08-20 01:28:40','','Kerry Nagle','','inherit','closed','closed','','kerry-nagle-2','','','2015-08-19 21:28:52','2015-08-20 01:28:52','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Kerry-Nagle.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(203,3,'2015-08-20 16:16:06','2015-08-20 20:16:06','Michelle currently runs product development for Infinite Biomedical Technologies (IBT), a small Baltimore medical device company that develops control systems and sensors for upper-limb myoelectric prostheses. As a biomedical engineer, Michelle began her professional career designing orthopedic implants and moved through several engineering roles that took her from innovation labs to the manufacturing floor. After a few years of plates and screws, she then returned to Johns Hopkins University for a MSE through the Center for Bioengineering Innovation where she focused on user-centered design for both advanced health systems and low resource global health settings. At IBT, she relishes the small company environment that runs the gamut of medical device development from hands-on prototyping to navigating complex regulatory requirements.','Michelle Zwernemann','','publish','closed','closed','','michelle-zwernemann','','','2015-09-15 13:33:52','2015-09-15 17:33:52','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=203',0,'speaker','',0),(207,4,'2015-08-25 15:37:07','2015-08-25 19:37:07','','DeborahLathen','','inherit','closed','closed','','deborahlathen','','','2015-08-25 16:01:20','2015-08-25 20:01:20','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/DeborahLathen.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(210,3,'2015-08-29 07:55:38','2015-08-29 11:55:38','<a href=\"http://technical.ly/baltimore/2015/08/28/info-women-tech-summit/\" target=\"_blank\">Read the article on Technical.ly Baltimore</a>\r\n','What you should know about the Women in Tech Summit','','publish','closed','closed','','what-you-should-know-about-the-women-in-tech-summit','','','2015-08-29 07:55:38','2015-08-29 11:55:38','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?p=210',0,'post','',0),(215,4,'2015-09-14 09:19:02','2015-09-14 13:19:02','Sarah Johnson started her IT career as a receptionist who asked why her company used pen and paper instead of a web application and ended up as the Manager of Technology. She learned web programming on the job with support from community tech user groups, eventually giving back to the same community by teaching with organizations like Girl Develop It and TechGirlz. After volunteering with TechGirlz as a teacher, committee member, and TechShopz Coach, Sarah was hired as the Community Outreach Manager, working to engage the community in and beyond Philadelphia to inspire girls to learn about technology.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSarah\'s social life consists of organizing and attending technology-related events in the Philadelphia area. She is a co-organizer of OpenAccessPHL, a network of civic technology enthusiasts and innovators, a member of the planning committee for the Women in Tech Summit, and an active member of the Code for Philly brigade of Code for America.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWhen not attending or planning a tech event, Sarah is co-organizing the Girl Geek Dinners monthly craft night or working on a sewing project.','Sarah Johnson','','publish','closed','closed','','sarah-johnson','','','2015-09-19 17:34:40','2015-09-19 21:34:40','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=215',0,'speaker','',0),(216,4,'2015-09-14 09:17:46','2015-09-14 13:17:46','','Sarah Johnson','','inherit','closed','closed','','sarah-johnson','','','2015-09-14 09:18:42','2015-09-14 13:18:42','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/Sarah-Johnson.jpg',0,'attachment','im