41:59','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/WITSPHL-15-panel.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(554,4,'2015-12-14 19:54:07','2015-12-15 00:54:07','The Women in Tech Summit is dedicated to providing a positive, harassment-free conference experience for everyone, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, age or religion. We do not tolerate harassment of conference participants in any form.  Conference participants include attendees, speakers, sponsors, exhibitors, volunteers and staff.\r\n\r\nSexual language and imagery is not appropriate for any conference venue, including talks. Harassment includes offensive verbal comments, sexual images in public spaces, deliberate intimidation, stalking, following, unwanted photography or recording, sustained disruption of talks or other events, inappropriate physical contact, and unwelcome sexual attention.\r\n\r\nParticipants asked to stop any harassing behavior are expected to comply immediately\r\n\r\nIf a participant engages in harassing behaviour, event organizers retain the right to take any actions to maintain a welcoming environment for all participants. This includes warning the offender or expulsion from the conference with no refund. Event organizers may take action to redress anything designed to, or with the clear impact of, disrupting the event or making the environment hostile for any participants.\r\n\r\nWe expect participants to follow these rules at all event venues and event-related social activities.\r\n\r\nIf you are being harassed, notice that someone else is being harassed, or have any other concerns, please report it immediately. You can report it to a member of the Women in Tech Summit committee, a volunteer or to the conference contacts listed below.  Women in Tech Summit committee and volunteers can be identified by their name badges.\r\n\r\nOur team will be happy to help you contact venue security, local law enforcement, local support services, provide escorts, or otherwise assist you to feel safe for the duration of the event. We value your attendance. We expect participants to follow these rules at all conference venues and conference-related social events. If you find this policy restrictive, please do not attend or speak at the conference.\r\n<h3>Conference contacts:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Gloria Bell,<a href=\"mailto:gloriabell@techgirlz.org\">gloriabell@techgirlz.org</a>  or via text at 215-645-2308</li>\r\n	<li>Tracey Welson-Rossman, <a href=\"mailto:twr@techgirlz.org\">twr@techgirlz.org</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHarassment policy adapted from the <a href=\"http://geekfeminism.wikia.com/wiki/Anti-harassment_policy_resources\">geek feminism wiki.</a>','Code of Conduct','','publish','closed','closed','','code-of-conduct','','','2015-12-14 20:01:06','2015-12-15 01:01:06','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?page_id=554',0,'page','',0),(556,3,'2015-12-14 20:04:58','2015-12-15 01:04:58',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','556','','','2016-06-01 20:06:28','2016-06-02 00:06:28','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?p=556',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),(557,3,'2015-12-14 21:12:45','2015-12-15 02:12:45','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sarah Johnson started her IT career as a receptionist who asked why her company used pen and paper instead of a web application and ended up as the Manager of Technology. She learned web programming on the job with support from community tech user groups, eventually giving back to the same community by teaching with organizations like Girl Develop It and TechGirlz. After volunteering with TechGirlz as a teacher, committee member, and TechShopz Coach, Sarah was hired as the Community Outreach Manager, working to engage the community in and beyond Philadelphia to inspire girls to learn about technology.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sarah\'s social life consists of organizing and attending technology-related events in the Philadelphia area. She is on the planning committee for the Women in Tech Summit, an active member of the Code for Philly brigade of Code for America, and has been an organizer of other civic engagement groups such as OpenAccessPHL.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\r\nWhen not attending or planning a tech event, Sarah is co-organizing the Girl Geek Dinners monthly craft night or working on a sewing project.</p>','Sarah Johnson','','publish','closed','closed','','sarah-johnson-2','','','2016-01-28 09:10:33','2016-01-28 14:10:33','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=557',0,'speaker','',0),(558,3,'2015-12-14 21:13:11','2015-12-15 02:13:11','Have you ever tried coding? If not, this is a great workshop for you! We\'ll use Blockly, a drag-and-drop interface, to create visual computer programs. The workshop content that we\'ll use is part of the TechShopz in a Box (TM) program from TechGirlz. So in addition to learning to code, you\'ll also learn how to take this content and teach it to middle school girls to encourage their interest in technology!','Learn to Code & Teach Middle School Girls','','publish','closed','open','','learn-to-code-teach-middle-school-girls','','','2016-02-22 21:29:26','2016-02-23 02:29:26','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=558',0,'session','',0),(559,3,'2015-12-14 21:17:56','2015-12-15 02:17:56','An accomplished human resource and talent executive, Grace’s work rests on what she has identified as the four cornerstones of leadership: relationships, reputation, results, and resilience. Using these pillars, CEOs, executives, and professionals elevate their leadership and transcend their perceived limitations to achieve sustained business and personal success. Whether she’s captivating audiences or coaching one-on-one, Grace’s leadership inspires change.\r\n\r\nA veteran of the telecommunications industry, Grace served as SVP of Talent and the first ever VP of Talent Management and Leadership Diversity at Comcast Cable Corporation, a Fortune 50 company headquartered in Philadelphia. Among her many innovative programs, Grace implemented a management process to identify top internal leaders and developed succession planning and leadership pathways. Over 3,000 Comcast directors now participate in this process annually.\r\n\r\nGrace began her career in retail, as one of Price Club’s first 300 employees. At only 26 years old, Grace successfully negotiated with the Teamsters Union and also led the East Coast division of Human Resources, growing from 20 employees to nearly 4,000 under her tenure. Grace later served as VP of Human Resources for Comcast Spotlight, a two billion dollar division of Comcast, founded and was president of Sterling Resource Group, and later was SVP of Human Resources at Lifetime Television. After 35 years in talent management, human resources, retail, and programming, Grace retired to launch Half The Sky Leadership for Women and continue her practice as a keynote speaker and consultant.\r\n\r\nA strong advocate for personal and professional development opportunities, especially for women and minorities, Grace’s influence extends to her volunteer work as well. For over a dozen years, she was the national facilitator of the Betsy Magness Leadership Program, a selective nine-month, intensive leadership curriculum for senior level women in the telecommunications industry. The only woman in the industry to have held this position, to date Grace has worked with and mentored over 600 executive woman leaders.\r\n\r\nIn 2013, Grace was selected to serve on the Board of the Girl Scouts of Eastern Pennsylvania. GSEP serves 41,000 girls in partnership with 15,000 volunteers in the nine county Philadelphia area. Today, 80 percent of women in leadership and executive roles in the U.S. were Girl Scouts. Girl Scout alumnae comprise 70 percent of women in the U.S. Congress.\r\n\r\nA sampling of Grace’s many honors and awards include: “Wonder Woman” by Multichannel News; “Women on the Move” by CableFax’s; “Women in Power” by DiversityPlus magazine; “Mentor of the Year” by WICT Northern California Chapter; and “Lucille Larkin Lifetime Achievement Award” by WICT Philadelphia Chapter. She was recently awarded the SmartCEO Brava Award for being a Top Philadelphia Female CEO.\r\n\r\nShe is a certified Birkman Consultant and also trained at the prestigious Center for Creative Leadership in Greensboro, NC, considered to be one of the best leadership programs in the United States. Grace earned her Master’s Degree in Human Resources from American University’s Kogod School of Business and Public Affairs. A sought-after keynote speaker and executive coach, Grace recently authored her second book, entitled <em>“The Confidence Effect” </em>published by AMACOM. Grace resides in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.','Grace Killelea','','publish','closed','closed','','grace-killelea','','','2016-02-19 15:39:41','2016-02-19 20:39:41','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=559',0,'speaker','',0),(562,3,'2015-12-15 12:06:03','2015-12-15 17:06:03','During this workshop students will install the open source software R and use it to practice drawing maps. We will begin by exploring spatial differences in worldwide gender roles and technology exports. Then we will switch our focus to the US and Pennsylvania, drawing maps to demonstrate gender differences in education and economic outcomes. Students will learn the required R code and receive tips for how to alter the code to draw other kinds of maps.\r\n\r\n<strong>Key Takeaways:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Step-by-Step instructions for installing R</li>\r\n	<li>Functioning R code snippets to combine other data into map data frames</li>\r\n	<li>Functioning R code snippets to draw a variety of maps</li>\r\n	<li>List of resources for doing more with maps</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Notes:</b> A laptop is required to participate in this workshop. Please install R and RStudio before the summit.\r\n<div>\r\n<div>Installing R and RStudio</div>\r\n· Go to <a href=\"https://cran.r-project.org/\" target=\"_blank\">https://cran.r-project.org/</a>\r\n· Select the correct download for your operating system and follow the instructions (you should have administrator privileges on your computer)\r\n· Refer to the Frequently Asked Questions if you get stuck\r\n· Go to <a href=\"https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/</a>\r\n· Select the correct installer and download it\r\n· Run the installation file\r\n· Run RStudio, it should detect your R installation\r\n· If you have any problems with RStudio, search for \"Troubleshooting Guide\" at <a href=\"http://rstudio.com/\" target=\"_blank\">rstudio.com</a></div>','Mapping with Open Source Software: Using R','','publish','closed','closed','','mapping-with-open-source-software-using-r','','','2016-03-28 11:35:58','2016-03-28 15:35:58','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=562',0,'session','',0),(563,3,'2015-12-15 12:11:53','2015-12-15 17:11:53','Work with a WordPress site? Unsure of how to take the step from your admin dash into PHP? In this talk, we\'ll be digging into PHP with something simple, yet practical: registering and using custom post types for your site. Custom post types are content types (i.e. \'Movies,\' \'Recipes,\' or \'Talk Sessions,\') that you can use to further organize your content, and query it around your site.\r\n\r\nPHP gives you greater control of your site, and frees you from some of WordPress\' limitations. This talk is for intermediate-level WordPress users, and is intended to be a jumping-off point for further PHP development.\r\n\r\n<strong>Key Takeaways:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Working in the functions.php file of your site</li>\r\n	<li>Registering custom post types there using a text editor of your choice, or WordPress\' on-site PHP editor</li>\r\n	<li>Adding your custom post type to your navigation bar</li>\r\n	<li>Creating a single-page and archive-page (think blog-style format) for your custom post type</li>\r\n	<li>Customizing these pages within the Loop by using display functions</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Planning to attend PHP workshop? First, you\'ll need to get access to the files that make up your site. </strong>\r\n\r\nThe process of doing this is called SFTP, or Safe File Transfer Protocol. It\'s how you get into the guts of your website.\r\n\r\n<strong>Install SFTP client on your laptop prior to workshop. Do not wait to install this during the workshop.</strong>\r\n• CyberDuck https://cyberduck.io/?l=en\r\n• Filezilla Client https://filezilla-project.org/\r\nSuccessfully connect at least one time to webhost prior to workshop.\r\n\r\n<strong>Here are 2 sample tutorials for getting started.</strong>\r\n<a href=\"https://mediatemple.net/community/products/dv/204643960/using-filezilla-for-ftp-sftp\" target=\"_blank\">https://mediatemple.net/community/products/dv/204643960/using-filezilla-for-ftp-sftp</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://wpengine.com/support/sftp/\" target=\"_blank\">https://wpengine.com/support/sftp/</a>\r\n\r\n<em>Feel free to Google more if they don\'t help you.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Here\'s the general idea of how to proceed:</strong>\r\n• Ask your webhost for proper credentials (Port, IP address, your username, and your password).\r\n• Test them in your FTP client.\r\n• If it\'s a success, a window will open listing each of the files of your site.\r\n• Create a new folder in your home directory, name it whatever you want to call your new project. Let\'s call it \'WITSPHP\'\r\n• Drag your wp-content folder from your SFTP window to the \'WITSPHP\' file.\r\n• Open \'WITSPHP\' in your favorite text editor*\r\n• You\'re ready for the workshop!\r\n\r\n<strong>*Selecting a Text Editor-Resource list</strong>\r\n<a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Learn/Common_questions/Available_text_editors\" target=\"_blank\">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Learn/Common_questions/Available_text_editors</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/articles/free-course-choosing-a-text-editor--cms-24510\" target=\"_blank\">http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/articles/free-course-choosing-a-text-editor--cms-24510</a>\r\n\r\nGet Desktop Server: \r\nhttps://serverpress.com/\r\n\r\nResources from Presentation:\r\n<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/14-wJyTQ1ZGQ5c4gMt-zA78lnaSw39_VbWi6gWR_86S0/edit\">Plugin text file</a> \r\n<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1oJJSrVlJXfRTMMB0_4URcQizktXNUMoxBvdL-BAIoG0/edit?ts=56ffcb3c#slide=id.p\">Slides from Becca</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Practical PHP: How to Back Away Slowly from Your WordPress Dashboard','','publish','closed','closed','','practical-php-how-to-back-away-slowly-from-your-wordpress-dashboard','','','2016-04-09 12:09:18','2016-04-09 16:09:18','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=563',0,'session','',0),(565,3,'2015-12-15 12:17:05','2015-12-15 17:17:05','Whether you’re a budding entrepreneur or an early stage startup, launching your own business isn’t easy – especially when your funds are limited. From idea to execution, kickstart your new business venture with thoughts from the region’s best successful entrepreneurs. Listen as this diverse panel of startup leaders provide tips and tools to get your startup off the ground and win over investors. Learn some of the biggest mistakes entrepreneurs make when pitching to angels and how to avoid those pitfalls.','How to get your startup off the ground and attract investors','','publish','closed','closed','','how-to-get-your-startup-off-the-ground-and-attract-investors','','','2016-04-10 10:40:50','2016-04-10 14:40:50','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=565',0,'session','',0),(566,3,'2015-12-15 12:44:40','2015-12-15 17:44:40','For over 15 years, Sherrilyn Billger, PhD has navigated the male-dominated waters of academic economics. She specializes in quantitative analyses of topics in education, labor, gender, race, and public policy. She loves to analyze big data sets and make charts that convey more information than a few sentences of text could. She has taught courses in labor, demographics, and econometrics to both undergraduates and graduates.','Sherrilyn Billger','','publish','closed','closed','','sherrilyn-billger','','','2015-12-15 16:54:34','2015-12-15 21:54:34','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=566',0,'speaker','',0),(567,4,'2015-12-15 14:55:53','2015-12-15 19:55:53','Elizabeth A. Hight enjoyed a career in the United States Navy and in Industry as a leader in information technology and cybersecurity. She graduated Magna Cum Laude from Huntingdon College and joined the Navy in 1977. Her duty stations ranged from major telecommunications and data commands both overseas and in the United States, two Combatant Command Staffs (i.e., US Space Command, US Strategic Command), an acquisition command, the Joint Staff, the Navy’s Headquarters staff (i.e., OPNAV), the Bureau of Naval Personnel, the Defense Information Systems Agency and the Joint Task Force Global Network Operations. Her responsibilities in these organizations ranged from leading operational units, launching communications satellites, authoring network/data/cybersecurity policy, developing and advocating budget submissions, interacting with the Congress, and managing/deploying personnel to meet global military requirements. She is a graduate of the Naval Postgraduate School with a Master’s Degree in Telecommunications Systems, The George Washington University with a Master’s Degree in Information Systems and the Defense Systems Management College.\r\n\r\nAfter retiring from the Navy in 2010, she joined the US Public Sector team of Hewlett Packard for four years where she served as the Vice President for Cybersecurity Solutions. While there, she renewed her relationships with governments and militaries around the world as they combat malicious actors in cyberspace providing end-to-end cybersecurity solutions.\r\n\r\nToday she serves as a member of the Virginia Commission on Cyber Security, the University of Maryland University College Task Force on Cybersecurity, and the Software Engineering Institute Board of Visitors. She also serves on the Boards of a publicly-traded real estate investment trust and a private company focused on cybersecurity.','Rear Admiral Elizabeth Hight','','publish','closed','closed','','rear-admiral-elizabeth-hight','','','2016-02-19 15:41:37','2016-02-19 20:41:37','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=567',0,'speaker','',0),(568,4,'2015-12-15 14:54:00','2015-12-15 19:54:00','','Elizabeth Hight','','inherit','closed','closed','','elizabethhight','','','2015-12-15 14:54:27','2015-12-15 19:54:27','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ElizabethHight.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(569,4,'2015-12-15 15:06:06','2015-12-15 20:06:06','Theresa Caragol has over 20 years of strategy and implementation experience in IT and telecommunications. She brings together a unique blend of skills and experience with extensive IT – hardware and software to enterprise, and partner ecosystems including resale and managed services as well as telecommunications experience. With experience from several IT vendors, she brings sales, channel, business development, P&amp;L and strategic alliances and consulting experience. She has served on multiple IT industry advisory boards and her insights are grounded in field experience, strategic design, practical application and operational expertise.\r\n\r\nTheresa founded TCC to assist organizations with their global go to market strategy and growth models. She contracts and consults with companies to help them with global strategy, go to market models, partner and channel development, market value propositions, M&amp;A successful integrations and leading change.\r\n\r\nFor the past 10 years, Theresa has held global Vice President Channels and Alliances leadership positions at Ciena and Extreme Networks where she has:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Led strategy and successful execution of worldwide channels and partnerships encompassing a base of more than 2,000 partners and 60+ distributors globally;</li>\r\n	<li>Built global partner routes-to-market that included global service provider managed services, strategic technology partners and OEM alliances</li>\r\n	<li>Developed industry-recognized channel partner programs</li>\r\n	<li>Led global sales, marketing and channel and 2-tier distribution organizations</li>\r\n	<li>Conducted multiple company acquisition integrations and successfully consolidated complete channel ecosystem mergers</li>\r\n	<li>Established partner–centric organizational cultures</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCaragol also brings go to market expertise in the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Channels and programs audits and benchmarking</li>\r\n	<li>Route to market models and strategies</li>\r\n	<li>Value and business proposition creation</li>\r\n	<li>Global channels and alliances partner programs strategy, design and execution</li>\r\n	<li>Global 2 tier distribution including: sales, selection, monitoring, rationalization</li>\r\n	<li>Global Strategic Alliances, Cloud and Managed Services partnership development and management</li>\r\n	<li>Partner profiling, recruitment and onboarding</li>\r\n	<li>Partner financial models</li>\r\n	<li>Sales compensation models</li>\r\n	<li>Global partner advisory/advocacy councils</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTheresa brings unique experience with various Technology &amp; Telecommunications industry types:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Hardware Vendors (OEM &amp; Technology Partnerships) Healthcare</li>\r\n	<li>Software Corporations Primary (K12) Education</li>\r\n	<li>Global System Integrators Research &amp; Higher Education</li>\r\n	<li>Regional Solutions Providers &amp; Sales Agents Government: Public Sector, US Federal Service Providers: Tier 1 Global, Emerging, Cloud Providers Manufacturing &amp; Retail</li>\r\n	<li>OEM &amp; Strategic Alliance Partnerships Two Tier Distributors Globally</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHer global work experience and deep partner relationships and both 1 and 2 tier distribution relationships transcend 25+ countries:\r\n\r\nEurope: UK, Germany, France, Spain, Nordics, Netherlands, Turkey, Italy, Poland, Slovenia,\r\n\r\nLATAM: Mexico, Brazil, Chile, Argentina, Columbia\r\n\r\nAsia: Australia, Israel, Hong Kong, India, Japan, China\r\n\r\nUS &amp; Canada\r\n\r\nTheresa’s 20+ years of experience in the technology industry also includes stints with IBM, Nortel, Bay Networks and Cambrian Systems. Theresa co-chairs a Baptie Channel Focus womens’ advisory board, which provides directional guidance for content and education to channel professionals. She serves on the advisory board of PerScholas, an initiative to bring underprivileged individuals into IT. She has also previously served on Friends of Guest House Non Profit Board, Comptia Women’s’ Forum Executive Council, and Virginia Tech’s College of Arts and Sciences Board.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, she was selected as one of 15 inaugural women for The Leadership Foundry, created by Women in Technology (WIT), to assist more women to serve on corporate boards in the Washington, D.C. area. Theresa has received numerous IT industry channel accolades recognizing her work:\r\n\r\n- 2014 CRN Top 50 Most Influential Channel Executives\r\n\r\n- 2013 CRN Top 10 Next Generation Channel Leaders\r\n\r\n- 2012-2104 CRN Top 100 Channel Chiefs\r\n\r\n- 2013 &amp; 2014 CRN Most Powerful Women of the Channel\r\n\r\n- 2011-2014 CRN Top Women of the Channel lists\r\n\r\n- 2015 Golden Bridge Gold (Top) Award for Best Program Director','Theresa Caragol','','publish','closed','closed','','theresa-caragol','','','2016-01-31 10:38:06','2016-01-31 15:38:06','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=569',0,'speaker','',0),(570,3,'2015-12-15 16:54:10','2015-12-15 21:54:10','','SherrilynBillger','','inherit','closed','closed','','sherrilynbillger','','','2015-12-15 16:54:22','2015-12-15 21:54:22','',566,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/SherrilynBillger.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(571,4,'2015-12-15 18:34:09','2015-12-15 23:34:09','Tracey is the founder of TechGirlz. She is also a founding member of, and Chief Marketing Officer for, Chariot Solutions, a Philadelphia-based Java and open source software development and consulting firm. Tracey has created the branding and marketing strategy for Chariot, helping it to grow from 10 employees in 2002 to 50. She is also responsible for managing the strategic planning process, as well as spearheading Chariot’s sales efforts.\r\n\r\nAfter graduating from Drexel, Tracey started her career in retail management and advertising sales. She learned about lead development, marketing, and distribution in these roles, but what she really learned was that she’s an entrepreneur at heart. In 1996, Tracey bought a New Jersey-based child transportation company called KangaKab. In 1999, with revenues at $2.5 million and having started a branch in Pennsylvania, Tracey sold KangaKab. As the director of sales &amp; marketing for accounting software provider Skylight Systems, Tracey developed and executed marketing and channel efforts around one of the first-ever hosted accounting products. This program supplemented the existing sales of RFS, Skylight’s server based flagship product. It was very early on for the web-hosted software concept, but several firms began to use this product for their clients.\r\n\r\nTracey is also the founder and current chair of the Emerging Technologies for the Enterprise Conference, (ETE), which is held in Philadelphia each year. ETE attracts world-renowned thought leaders in cutting-edge technologies and serves as a community forum for regional technology companies. Tracey is one of the founding board members of Philadelphia Startup Leaders, a regional organization dedicated to growing technology startup businesses (www.phillystartupleaders.org).','Tracey Welson-Rossman','','publish','closed','closed','','tracey-welson-rossman-2','','','2016-01-31 10:37:14','2016-01-31 15:37:14','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=571',0,'speaker','',0),(572,4,'2015-12-16 13:10:45','2015-12-16 18:10:45','','SrutiCheedalla','','inherit','closed','closed','','sruticheedalla300x300','','','2015-12-16 13:13:30','2015-12-16 18:13:30','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/SrutiCheedalla300x300.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(573,4,'2015-12-16 13:14:08','2015-12-16 18:14:08','Sruti Cheedalla is a Senior Web Developer at The Washington Post. She focuses on developing applications with the MEAN (MongoDB, Express, Angular, Node.js) stack. Sruti started out as a front end developer and has evolved into a full stack developer working on everything from CSS to maintaining infrastructure on Amazon Web Services. When she is not busy working on innovative products at The Post, she enjoys attending and speaking at tech conferences. Most recently, she helped organize The Washington Post’s first Developer Day and along with two of her colleagues, presented a session on the MEAN Stack at MongoDB World 2015.','Sruti Cheedalla','','publish','closed','closed','','sruti-cheedalla','','','2016-01-31 10:35:58','2016-01-31 15:35:58','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=573',0,'speaker','',0),(574,3,'2015-12-16 19:55:36','2015-12-17 00:55:36','Opening the Black Box - Hardware Tear-Down of a Digital Camera	\"Have you ever wondered how exactly the devices we use in our daily lives are constructed? We can all learn to use a digital camera, even if we don\'t all know exactly how the digital signal processor inside of it works.\r\n\r\nRather than follow the traditional \"\"build-up\"\" approach to teaching, in this workshop we will take the opposite tack and do a hardware \"\"tear-down\"\". Let\'s peel back the layers of abstraction and look inside the black box of hardware. Nothing works merely by magic, and the more familiar we are with the pieces that compose electronic devices, the better we will be able to build newer and greater ones without being intimidated by their complexity.\r\n\r\nParticipants will be provided with used digital cameras. We will work together to take them apart, look inside, and see their composition at an embedded systems level. What makes them similar? How are they different and why? Bring your curiosity and expect to use your hands and your minds to do some investigating. Let\'s take the mystery out of hardware!\"	','Opening the Black Box - Hardware Tear-Down of a Digital Camera','','publish','closed','open','','opening-the-black-box-hardware-tear-down-of-a-digital-camera','','','2016-02-25 21:56:33','2016-02-26 02:56:33','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=574',0,'session','',0),(575,3,'2015-12-16 20:00:16','2015-12-17 01:00:16','Gabrielle Trotter is a University of Pennsylvania graduate and Embedded Software Engineer at BuLogics, Inc. In her short tenure at BuLogics, Gabrielle has already led multiple teams of engineers to success across a dozen design/build projects. These projects include: An international home automation wireless multi-protocol gateway, a wireless outdoor lighting system, the Root/Ohneka Farms Internet of Things smart countertop gardening system, multiple wireless thermostats for a leading manufacturer of smart thermostats,  and numerous IoT devices, including but not limited to motion sensors, door/window sensors, sirens, and more.\r\n','Gabrielle Trotter','','publish','closed','closed','','gabrielle-trotter','','','2015-12-16 20:34:50','2015-12-17 01:34:50','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=575',0,'speaker','',0),(577,3,'2015-12-16 20:05:25','2015-12-17 01:05:25','Ashley is a programmer and consultant in DC specializing in security and forensics. She is an advocate for women and minorities in STEM fields and frequently teaches for local schools and women\'s groups.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Ashley Holtz','','publish','closed','closed','','ashley-holtz-2','','','2015-12-16 20:33:53','2015-12-17 01:33:53','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=577',0,'speaker','',0),(578,3,'2015-12-16 20:07:36','2015-12-17 01:07:36','Security Tools So Simple Your Grandma Could Hack You! \"The best way to learn about security is by trying out exploits in a controlled environment. This workshop is intended for programmers of all levels, and non-programmers alike. Attendees will walk away with the ability to explain the most common web exploits and hands-on knowledge of two must-have web security tools.\r\n\r\n<b>Note:</b> A Windows laptop is needed to fully participate in this workshop. Attendees without a Windows laptop can still attend but will miss out on some of the hands-on activities.\r\n\r\nRequired Downloads:\r\na) Wireshark: https://www.wireshark.org/download.html\r\nb) OWASP ZAP: https://github.com/zaproxy/zaproxy/wiki/Downloads\r\nc) Firefox: https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/new/\r\n\r\nAgenda:\r\n1) First, we\'ll go through the top ten web exploits from OWASP (Open Web Application Security Project). We\'ll learn about cross-site scripting, bad server configurations, \r\nauthentication issues, and more.\r\n2) Next, we\'ll do some browser-hacking and see what websites record about our actions. We\'ll also attempt to carry out some script-based exploits manually.\r\n3) We\'ll do some cursory scanning and recon of our target, including operating system and application fingerprinting.\r\n4) Finally, we\'ll use OWASP ZAP to automate some attacks, attempt to hack a password, and send some spam.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Security Tools So Simple Your Grandma Could Hack You!','','publish','closed','closed','','security-tools-so-simple-your-grandma-could-hack-you','','','2016-04-07 16:16:01','2016-04-07 20:16:01','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=578',0,'session','',0),(579,3,'2015-12-16 20:12:59','2015-12-17 01:12:59','Nisa Amoils is an angel investor, advisor and former entrepreneur. She is a member of New York Angels. She invests in a variety of technology and is the co-chair of the frontier technology committee which encompasses AI/VR, robotics, drones, driverless cars, autonomous innovations etc. She also has sector expertise in entertainment, beauty, marketplaces and digital media.\r\n\r\nShe has startup operational experience in areas such as strategic and digital marketing, business development, product and package development, distribution, staffing, fundraising, management and legal. She currently invests in and/or sits on Boards of startups and is a judge/panelist on CNBC, MSNBC and Fox, and does regular speaking and podcasts.\r\n\r\nPrior to investing, she spent many years at media companies, including Time Warner and NBC Universal, looking at Internet 1.0 deals and executing strategic partnerships with film and television on behalf of Fortune 500 brands.\r\n\r\nShe holds a BBA (business) degree from the University of Michigan and a law degree from the University of Pennsylvania, where she serves on the Board of the Design School. She is a mentor at the Wharton Entrepreneurship Program and judges student competitions.','Nisa Amoils','','publish','closed','closed','','nisa-amoils','','','2016-01-20 08:45:54','2016-01-20 13:45:54','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=579',0,'speaker','',0),(580,3,'2015-12-16 20:34:32','2015-12-17 01:34:32','','gabrielle_trotter','','inherit','closed','closed','','gabrielle_trotter','','','2015-12-16 20:34:45','2015-12-17 01:34:45','',575,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/gabrielle_trotter.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(581,4,'2015-12-22 17:18:16','2015-12-22 22:18:16','Camille Stewart is a Cyber and Technology Law Attorney, currently working for the Department of Homeland Security focusing on cyber, critical infrastructure and resilience policy. Prior to working at DHS, Camille spent a number of years as the Senior Manager of Legal Affairs at Cyveillance, Inc., a cyber security company. While at Cyveillance, Camille navigated legal and policy challenges with and identified solutions for cyber-related issues such as data privacy, incident response, Internet governance, cyber security, new gTLDs, social media law &amp; policy, and intellectual property protections online for Fortune 500 and Global 2000 companies. Camille represented Cyveillance to Internet Corporation for Assigned Names &amp; Numbers (ICANN) and was an active member of the Business Constituency pushing Internet governance policy. In addition to handling the company\'s legal and policy portfolio, she managed all Intellectual Property related services and a team of intelligence analysts.\r\n\r\nCamille also founded a legal consultancy, MarqueLaw, PLLC, &amp; a blog, <a href=\"http://thedigitalcounselor.com/\">TheDigitalCounselor.com</a>, as avenues to make cyber and intellectual property issues accessible to entrepreneurs and the less than technically savvy.\r\n\r\nCamille enjoys volunteering and is involved in a number of professional, social &amp; civic organizations including being an Internet Law &amp; Policy Foundry Fellow and a member of YWCA\'s Young Women\'s Leadership Council.','Camille Stewart','','publish','closed','closed','','camille-stewart','','','2016-01-31 10:26:59','2016-01-31 15:26:59','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=581',0,'speaker','',0),(582,4,'2015-12-17 11:42:35','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Tiffany Li is a Privacy Fellow at the Wikimedia Foundation. She is a technology attorney and a Certified Information Privacy Professional (CIPP/E, CIPP/US, CIPT, CIPM). She holds a J.D. from Georgetown University Law Center, where she was a Global Law Scholar, and a B.A. from University of California Los Angeles, where she was a Norma J. Ehrlich Alumni Scholar.\r\n\r\nShe has previously worked for corporations including Amazon, Ask.com, and Fubon Financial Holding Company (Taiwan/Hong Kong), as well as public sector organizations including the U.S. Department of State and the Federal Communications Commission. She is also a Board Member for the International Association of Privacy Professionals Women Leading Privacy Advisory Board.','Tiffany Li','','draft','closed','closed','','','','','2015-12-17 11:42:35','2015-12-17 16:42:35','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=582',0,'speaker','',0),(583,4,'2015-12-22 17:07:27','2015-12-22 22:07:27','Gabriella is a DC-based intellectual property attorney of Silicon Valley career origins, with multi-faceted experience in the tech industry.She’s served as outside counsel, worked in-house at technology companies in Silicon Valley, advised tech start-ups, clerked for a magistrate judge,and actively brings the technology community together through dynamic programming. Prior to her career in tech, Gabriella worked closely with the Arizona Board of Regents as an advocate for higher education, women’s rights, and LGBTQ rights initiatives at the University of Arizona.','Gabriella Ziccarelli','','publish','closed','closed','','gabriella-ziccarelli-2','','','2016-02-12 10:18:24','2016-02-12 15:18:24','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=583',0,'speaker','',0),(585,5,'2015-12-25 22:37:58','2015-12-26 03:37:58','Fiercely driven, wildly curious, and shamelessly goofy, Becca is an advocate for women in tech and for hands-on learning. As a member of TechGirlz\' leadership team since its founding, she\'s served multiple roles within the org: from website development, to marketing strategy, to directing the annual Entrepreneur Summer Camp. Becca is also a student intern at Chariot Solutions, where she learns JavaScript under the guidance of Chariot\'s developers. Her work here has gotten her comfortable with PHP and the many quirks of WordPress.\r\n\r\nBecca likes to bike and has a huge weakness for Mexican food. You can find her walking all over Philly with her Anatolian Shepherd, Tuco, or Instagramming street art.','Becca Refford','','publish','closed','closed','','becca-refford','','','2015-12-25 22:37:58','2015-12-26 03:37:58','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=585',0,'speaker','',0),(586,5,'2015-12-25 22:35:36','2015-12-26 03:35:36','Since graduating in early 2015 with a BS in sustainable urbanism Dawn has pursued a career in the world of civic technology. Her entry point was the incredible community that organizes around it, and it continues to show her more and more about the world and herself.\r\n\r\nShe works with passionate professionals, dedicated nonprofit and community groups, and municipal partners to make Philly a better place for all the people living here.\r\n\r\nOther fixations and distractions of Dawn\'s include biking and walking through Philly, reading nonfiction/graphic novels, sketching ideas and playing with digital art tools, cooking, and poorly managing cuteness aggression.','Dawn McDougall','','publish','closed','closed','','dawn-mcdougall','','','2015-12-29 17:52:42','2015-12-29 22:52:42','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=586',0,'speaker','',0),(587,5,'2015-12-25 22:26:40','2015-12-26 03:26:40','Jessica Hall is the Director of the Innovate Practice at 3Pillar Global, where helps companies get the right products to market quickly. Previously she built the UX team at CEB and led the creation of the Newseum’s interactive exhibits and website. She is a contributor to Product Development Success and blogs at Hallway Studio. Her work has been recognized by the Web Marketing Association, American Association of Museums, The Webby Awards, Time and Forbes. She holds a Masters in Design and Digital Media from the University of Edinburgh and a BA in Journalism from American University.','Jessica Hall','','publish','closed','closed','','jessica-hall','','','2016-03-02 12:24:07','2016-03-02 17:24:07','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=587',0,'speaker','',0),(588,5,'2015-12-25 22:33:11','2015-12-26 03:33:11','Liz has a passion for research and design. She is the Cofounder and Lead UX Designer at Webjunto, a Philadelphia based mobile and web design company. Over the past 15 years, she has worked on a wide range of projects including researching motivation theory, cognitive learning theories, and user experience design. Liz also has experience with both graphic design and front-end development (i.e. HTML5, CSS, Javascript).','Liz Brown','','publish','closed','closed','','liz-brown','','','2015-12-25 22:33:11','2015-12-26 03:33:11','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=588',0,'speaker','',0),(589,5,'2015-12-25 22:56:38','2015-12-26 03:56:38','Mavis Pogue is a full-time faculty member in the Educational Support Services – Learning Labs at Community College of Philadelphia. Her expertise is in Computer Technologies. Mavis has worked as a training consultant and trainer for Corporations as well as holding administrative positions over the past 20 years. She specializes in office products, HTML5, CSS3 and Adobe Creative Suite along with rapid e-learning software (Captivate, Articulate). She holds three degrees in Computer Technologies all with summa cum laude honors: an A.A.S. in Internet Options and Web Development (2004) from Community College of Philadelphia, a B.S. in Technology Management (2009) from Peirce College and a M.S. in Instructional Technology Management (2011) from LaSalle University. She holds certifications in Adobe Dreamweaver CS6 and Flash C6. Mavis is also a founding member of the Golden Key International Honour Society at LaSalle University. Presently, she is pursuing a doctorate in e-learning at Northcentral University.','Mavis Pogue','','publish','closed','closed','','mavis-pogue','','','2015-12-25 22:57:35','2015-12-26 03:57:35','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=589',0,'speaker','',0),(590,5,'2015-12-25 22:40:06','2015-12-26 03:40:06','Melissa Hartz is passionate about making information beautiful, accessible, and easy to understand. After graduating with a BA in Communications and Journalism, she fell into a job in Big Data and has never looked back.\r\n\r\nAs a Data Analyst at The Wharton School, Melissa uses data visualization to procure and present insights about students and alumni at the University of Pennsylvania.\r\n\r\nShe is a distance runner, traveler, and voracious reader.','Melissa Hartz','','publish','closed','closed','','melissa-hartz','','','2016-01-15 15:02:38','2016-01-15 20:02:38','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=590',0,'speaker','',0),(591,5,'2015-12-27 08:32:52','2015-12-27 13:32:52','Lois Bruckner has been entrenched in the technology space for most of her career. Her passion is doing things that have not been done before, by leading teams and initiatives involved in innovation. Currently, she is a director at SAP America in the North America Services Center of Excellence, where she develops business for professional services. She also built and ran a start-up consulting practice for SAP. Convinced that wisely deployed enterprise software is an essential competitive advantage, Lois has led top-name companies in their journey to implement SAP customer relationship management software. Previously, she led new product development for a bar-coding division of Avery Dennison, in the apparel industry. She volunteers as a coach and judge for high-school and college-student business-plan competitions. Lois holds an MBA from the Kellogg School, Northwestern University with a concentration in marketing and corporate finance.','Lois Bruckner','','publish','closed','closed','','lois-bruckner','','','2015-12-27 08:32:52','2015-12-27 13:32:52','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=591',0,'speaker','',0),(592,5,'2015-12-27 08:34:30','2015-12-27 13:34:30','Amanda Lange is a Technical Evangelist for Microsoft in the Philadelpha/Baltimore area. She is also a part-time video game critic for the web site <a href=\"http://www.tap-repeatedly.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.tap-repeatedly.com</a>. Her current interests include the Internet of Things, gamification, and how games and technology can promote health. She has done academic research on game development and games and health applications. She has worked for Schell Games, Idle Media Inc, and Michigan State University where she worked on subjects as diverse as augmented reality and project management for mobile gaming.','Amanda Lange','','publish','closed','closed','','amanda-lange-2','','','2015-12-27 08:34:30','2015-12-27 13:34:30','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=592',0,'speaker','',0),(593,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Yasmine is fueled by a passion to leverage technology for good. She\'s the CEO of ROAR for Good, a B-corp aimed at helping protect women using smart jewelry and education. She\'s also the co-leader of Girl Develop It Philadelphia, a non-profit aimed at lessening the gender gap in technology. In addition, she sits on the board of Coded by Kids, a non-profit that helps inner city youth learn how to code.','Yasmine Mustafa','','publish','closed','closed','','yasmine-mustafa','','','2016-01-27 16:56:37','2016-01-27 21:56:37','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=593',0,'speaker','',0),(594,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','TBA','Laura Spiekerman','','private','closed','closed','','laura-spiekerman','','','2016-01-18 15:20:35','2016-01-18 20:20:35','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=594',0,'speaker','',0),(595,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Ellen is passionate about innovation and about helping build great companies in Philadelphia. She serves as the Executive Director of Temple University\'s Fox School of Business Innovation and Entrepreneurship Institute, and an Assistant Professor of Entrepreneurship. She is also the Executive Director of Robin Hood Ventures (www.robinhoodventures.com), a leading angel group helping to fuel startup growth in the Philadelphia region. She is very active in the Philadelphia startup community, supporting Philly Startup Leaders, Philly Tech Meetup, and the Alliance of Women Entrepreneurs.\r\n\r\nPreviously, Ellen was the COO and co-founder of VisionMine (www.visionmine.com), which provides a specialized Open Innovation portal to large corporations.\r\n\r\nEllen has more than 25 years of experience creating strong teams and building strong leaders for emerging companies as well as Fortune 500 clients. She has been a Managing Director and Founder of Antiphony Partners, LLC, a strategic consulting firm that specializes in helping companies create sustainable value through innovation. She was involved in the growth of Investor Force, a provider of technology-based solutions for institutional investment professionals, where she created the company\'s initial human resources department, facilitated strategic planning, and managed the organizational aspects of the company\'s mergers and acquisitions. Additionally, she spent twelve years at Shared Medical Systems where she was responsible for initiatives encompassing organizational development, customer support and corporate communications. She was also a senior consultant for Andersen Consulting.\r\n\r\nEllen graduated from The Wharton School with a B.S. in economics.','Ellen Weber','','publish','closed','closed','','ellen-weber','','','2016-01-29 22:51:06','2016-01-30 03:51:06','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=595',0,'speaker','',0),(596,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Cecily is a writer who specializes in Content Marketing and Social Media Management through her agency, Double Good Media. She geeks out over helping companies grow. For ten years she wrote a personal blog where she shared entirely too much information publicly. As the internet grew up, so did she, and she shuttered her blog in 2014. Today she still writes online in various places like Ravishly, Your Tango, and Medium. She works as a personal coach to writers through Coach.me. Cecily lives in Philadelphia.','Cecily Kellogg','','publish','closed','closed','','cecily-kellogg-3','','','2016-02-06 16:56:24','2016-02-06 21:56:24','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=596',0,'speaker','',0),(597,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Seema Thomas is Vice President of solution strategy at hybris, an SAP company and is responsible for Commerce Solution Strategy and Go To Market. Seema is passionate about innovation and innovation adoption. Outside of SAP, Seema is an adjunct professor and teaches in the Villanova School of Business at Villanova University. She earned her MBA from Villanova University and a Bachelor of Engineering in Computer Sciences.','Seema Thomas','','publish','closed','closed','','seema-thomas','','','2016-02-06 16:57:14','2016-02-06 21:57:14','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=597',0,'speaker','',0),(598,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Beah is the Chief Product Office at Ticketleap, a center city startup. Her career in tech started in California at Google, where she worked in Search and later Publisher Ads as a Product Manager. She left Google in 2013 to join the Philadelphia tech community and to help it grow.','Beah Burger-Lenehan','','publish','closed','closed','','beah-burger-lenehan','','','2016-02-06 16:58:02','2016-02-06 21:58:02','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=598',0,'speaker','',0),(599,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Katy has spent her entire career in marketing, working for a variety of successful agencies in the Philadelphia area. In 1999 she joined i-FRONTIER, one of the first digital ad agencies. Katy was part of the leadership team that led i-FRONTIER through multiple acquisitions over a 15-year period helping to increase the agency\'s annual revenue by over $28 million during that time. Her responsibilities grew as i-FRONTIER became part of Razorfish in 2003, ultimately leading the Philadelphia office as the SVP Managing Director. Katy was also a member of the global Razorfish leadership team that included the leaders from all 19 global offices. Change has been a hallmark of her career as she evolved from Client Services to general agency management, and from traditional advertising to digital marketing. Katy is now a Partner, Managing Director at Shiny, a full service marketing agency whose mission is to create engagement in this age of distraction. Clients include AstraZeneca, Barclaycard US, College Ave Student Loans, El Diablo Burritos and Johnson &amp; Johnson.','Katy Thorbahn','','publish','closed','closed','','katy-thorbahn','','','2016-02-06 16:58:58','2016-02-06 21:58:58','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=599',0,'speaker','',0),(600,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','From large public companies to kitchen table startups, companies turn to Bobbie Carlton for help understanding how the worlds of entrepreneurs, startups and innovation intersect with marketing, social media and community building. The creator of Innovation Nights, Bostons beloved social media driven product launch party (more than 800 new products launched), Bobbies background in corporate public relations and marketing allows her to help companies recognize and capitalize on the opportunities presented by the innovation economy and social media driven communities. Whether your organization wants to think like a startup or connect to the $48.3 billion venture capitalists invested in 4,356 deals in 2014; the HR department is putting in place a recruitment strategy or the VP of Innovation looking to connect with the global startup community, Bobbie can help. Bobbie Carlton, founder of Carlton PR &amp; Marketing Innovation Nights and Innovation Women, is an award-winning marketing, PR and social media professional, as well as a sought-after speaker, corporate and startup adviser. Bobbie and the Innovation Nights community have helped to launch more than 800 new products which have collectively raised more than $1 billion in funding. Find out more at Innovation Nights. Bobbies latest venture, Innovation Women, is a new online visibility bureau for entrepreneurial, innovative and technical women. Carlton PR &amp; Marketing allows Bobbie to work with a select group of PR &amp; Marketing professionals to support startups and small businesses. Follow Bobbie on Twitter as <a href=\"http://twitter.com/BobbieC\" target=\"_blank\">@BobbieC</a>, <a href=\"http://twitter.com/WomenInno\" target=\"_blank\">@WomenInno</a> <a href=\"http://twitter.com/MassInno\" target=\"_blank\">@MassInno</a>','Bobbie Carlton','','publish','closed','closed','','bobbie-carlton','','','2015-12-27 08:11:54','2015-12-27 13:11:54','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=600',0,'speaker','',0),(603,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Peg Meadow has been a leader in health information technology for over 40 years and has excelled in designing and validating complex solutions and projects in new markets. The solutions were in areas of software and process implementations, application, new service line and related methodology development in new healthcare initiatives such as health policy advocacy, EHR certification, managed care, payers, pharmaceutical and clinical research.\r\n\r\nShe joined Children’s Hospital in Philadelphia in May 2015 as an Information Services Strategist. She provides consulting services for developing portfolio strategies in partnership with senior IS leader(s) and strategic consulting within IS. This includes high level assessments determining the current state, future state, gaps and recommendations on solution alternatives. Immediately before joining CHOP, Peg was an independent healthcare consultant for Christiana Care Health System, DE, as Project Director over the implementation of technology to support their new Medicare CMMI bundles. She also worked for the Bipartisan Policy Center, DC, providing research and bipartisan policy recommendations on interoperability.\r\n\r\nPeg worked for a leading HIT Vendor in various roles for the majority of her career and whose latest position was the Director of Government &amp; Industry Affairs. Her highlight in this role was securing the Company’s CEO, as the only HIT vendor to testify to the Congressional Senate Finance Committee. Peg laid the groundwork for setting him up with the congressional senior staff as a knowledgeable and trusted resources which established the Company as the experts.','Margaret Meadow','','publish','closed','closed','','margaret-meadow','','','2016-01-29 21:47:20','2016-01-30 02:47:20','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=603',0,'speaker','',0),(604,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','','Deborah Yogel','','draft','open','open','','deborah-yogel','','','2015-12-19 21:42:57','2015-12-20 02:42:57','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=604',0,'speaker','',0),(605,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Gayle Stidsen Smith is the Senior Director of IS PARC and HIM applications at The Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia (CHOP). She leads this IS department in supporting all IS functions for Patient Access, Health Information Management and Revenue Cycle applications. Gayle has proudly worked at CHOP for the last 14 years, building upon experiences and prior roles including Systems Manager, Lead Application Coordinator for Revenue Cycle and Lead System Analyst. She is a passionate, driven leader and collaborator across the institution and with external partners focuses on delivering excellence to support the ideal patient experience. She actively leads her team to improve workflow and efficiencies, always partnering with operational leadership to ensure the technology supports the business or clinical need. Gayle is also a mentor to staff and colleagues and finds fulfillment in building capabilities and identifying stretch goals for continuous learning and development.','Gayle Stidsen-Smith','','publish','closed','closed','','gayle-stidsen-smith','','','2016-01-29 21:49:57','2016-01-30 02:49:57','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=605',0,'speaker','',0),(606,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','As the Director of Nursing Technology and Informatics at the Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia (CHOP), Kimberly is responsible for leading and establishing the informatics strategic agenda for the Department of Nursing, Respiratory Care and Neurodiagnostic Services. She works in partnership with the CIO, CMIO, CNO and Nursing leadership to provide the vision and strategy for clinical information systems across the organization. Kimberly is responsible for integrating clinical knowledge, reducing variation and duplication, creating standardization, and designing tools to create highly reliable data processes. Additionally, Kimberly is responsible to talent development and expanding the reach of depth of the department and is redesigning the Nursing Informatics Service model. Kimberly has worked at CHOP for 5 years and very successfully served as an Informatics Nurse Specialist and the Program Director.\r\n\r\nPrior to joining The Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, Kimberly was a System Administrator at The Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania where she led the Woman’s Health Department in the development, training and implementation Centricity Perinatal, the electronic medical record for Labor and Delivery. In 2006, Kimberly built the electronic medical record and trained over 200 staff members for a highly successful big bang implementation.\r\n\r\nKimberly earned a Bachelor of Science in Nursing from the University Of Maryland School Of Nursing, a Master of Information Services from the University of Phoenix and is certified in Nursing Informatics by the American Nurses Credentialing Center. Kimberly is also certified in EpicCare Inpatient Clinical Documentation.','Kimberly Burress','','publish','closed','closed','','kimberly-burress','','','2016-01-29 22:07:40','2016-01-30 03:07:40','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=606',0,'speaker','',0),(607,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Kristen is a Cybersecurity Consultant for PwC Advisory based in Philadelphia, PA. She is a US Army Signal Corps veteran who specialized in Communication Security. Before joining PwC in 2008 as an Information Security consultant, Kristen served in the US Army Signal Corps stationed at Schofield Barracks, Hawaii specializing in war-time communications security and cryptography. She started her PwC career performing attack &amp; penetration testing and social engineering. Today, she works with clients in Technology, Telecommunications and Entertainment &amp; Media organizations helping them design, implement and measure the effectiveness of their Cybersecurity program, operating model and architecture. She has presented to Board of Directors on the impact of information security and how to prioritize investments to best mitigate risk. Kristen is a Drexel University graduate and holds several information security related certifications.','Kristen Maynes','','publish','closed','closed','','kristin-maynes','','','2016-01-07 18:28:03','2016-01-07 23:28:03','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=607',0,'speaker','',0),(608,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Liv Erickson is a virtual and augmented reality evangelist and developer at Microsoft. She has experience building for both virtual and augmented platforms, including the Oculus Rift and Meta Glass, and taught an introductory virtual reality development course at the University of Bremens Informatica Feminale summer program this past August. She has previously spoken on virtual reality on the web at JSConf Budapest, and presented two talks on VR technologies at the 2015 Grace Hopper Celebration of Women in Computing.','Liv Erickson','','publish','closed','closed','','liv-erickson','','','2015-12-27 08:23:28','2015-12-27 13:23:28','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=608',0,'speaker','',0),(609,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','SiNae Pitts, PhD is Founder and CEO of AMMO, short for Amphetamobile, LLC, a 100% woman-owned mobile technology company in Philadelphia. SiNae is an entrepreneur with a passion for creating user-centric, elegant tech that is online, mobile and good for the world. SiNae earned a PhD in Neuroscience from Columbia University and has published in several peer-reviewed journals and is an avid international foodie and cook. Since the App store opened in Fall of 2008, AMMO has been guided by scientific rigor and understanding of how to present complex information and meaningful use workflows and tools, to bring mobile apps and mobile sites to life. Clients for AMMOs consulting, design, development and licensing include national and international scholarly and medical publishers, such as the New England Journal of Medicine (NEJM), American College of Chest Physicians (CHEST), the World Bank, Thomson Reuters and Elsevier. AMMO\'s mobile publishing platforms not only include front end, native mobile apps for iOS and Android devices and mobile optimized webs sites, but also easy to use content management systems (CMS\'s) on the backend.','SiNae Pitts','','publish','closed','closed','','sinae-pitts','','','2015-12-27 08:31:42','2015-12-27 13:31:42','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=609',0,'speaker','',0),(610,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Susan Tabor Kleiman, JD, is the Founder of Your Professional Writer™ and a Lecturer in Management Communication in the University of Pennsylvania’s Wharton School of Business MBA and Executive MBA programs. Susan has worked in nearly every industry sector: government, private business, nonprofit, and academia. She specializes in creating persuasive writings including LinkedIn profiles about executives, entrepreneurs, and job seekers around the world and in the process help them to uncover and articulate their strengths, hone their message, and portray themselves in a compelling way to their target audience. Among her many conference appearances, Susan has spoken at the Pennsylvania Conference for Women, WICT National Leadership Conference, and Philly Tech Week. She also delivers workshops to a range of groups at various including to college and graduate students and at university alumni events. Media appearances as a LinkedIn expert include MSNBC’s Your Business with JJ Ramberg, Good Day Philadelphia, Clear Channel Radio, More.com, and the Huffington Post. A former trial lawyer, Susan volunteers as an Attorney Advisor to a high school mock trial team in suburban Philadelphia.','Susan Tabor-Kleiman','','publish','closed','closed','','susan-tabor-kleiman','','','2016-01-25 19:05:34','2016-01-26 00:05:34','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=610',0,'speaker','',0),(611,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Eloise Young has been the Chief Information Officer of the Philadelphia Gas Works since August 2007. She brings more than 20 years of experience to the position. As CIO, Young is responsible for delivering IT capabilities to PGW’s 1,600+ employees. Prior to her appointment, she served in a number of positions in PGW’s Information Services Department including Director of Technical Strategy and Support, Manager of Systems Services, System Administrator, DBA, and developer. A native Philadelphian, she loves her city and enjoys doing volunteer work for area community groups. Young received a 2015 Executive Management Award from Philadelphia SmartCEO and was named one of the 2014 Top Influential Women in Corporate America by Savoy Magazine. In 2011 she was received a Champions of Impact award from the United Way of Southeastern Pennsylvania and was named one of the \"Most Powerful and Influential Women in Pennsylvania\" by the National Diversity Council. In addition, Young belongs to the Network of Women in Computer Technology (NWCT) and the American Association of Blacks in Energy (AABE). She is also a Leadership Philadelphia Core Class 2010 alumnus, former Chair of the Green Grid’s Utility Task Force and a lifetime member of the Black Data Processing Professionals (BDPA).','Eloise Young','','publish','closed','closed','','eloise-young','','','2016-01-21 14:00:42','2016-01-21 19:00:42','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=611',0,'speaker','',0),(612,5,'2015-12-19 21:27:51','2015-12-20 02:27:51','Arushi Srivastava is the Director of Digital Experience practice of NTT DATA Americas. She leads several initiatives around IoT, Analytics, Digital Engagement and Design Thinking. She advises corporate leaders on architecting next generation enterprise solutions which aim at being Social by Design and result in Pervasive Experience.','Arushi Srivastava','','publish','closed','closed','','arushi-srivastava','','','2015-12-27 08:42:56','2015-12-27 13:42:56','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=612',0,'speaker','',0),(615,4,'2015-12-22 15:44:38','2015-12-22 20:44:38','<div>This hands-on workshop will introduce participants to key aspects in a product discovery process, combining ideas from user experience, Lean startup and agile development.</div>\r\n<div>Product discovery can be used in both business and non-business contexts. To demonstrate this, we will share our experience using it for planning a Halloween party for 4th graders and facilitate an agile game to give you a taste for product discovery steps.</div>\r\n<div>Join this session to practice identifying user personas, building a user story map of a product and envisioning a solution through the eyes of the users.</div>\r\n<div>Whether your product is for a bunch of 9 year old kids or for real business stakeholders, user story mapping will set you up for success. Learn it today and teach your kids too, prepare them for agile future!</div>','Discover Your Winning Product with User Story Mapping','','publish','closed','closed','','discover-your-winning-product-with-user-story-mapping','','','2016-03-05 16:32:21','2016-03-05 21:32:21','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=session&#038;p=615',0,'session','',0),(616,4,'2015-12-22 10:39:19','2015-12-22 15:39:19','','EricaIndman_WIT','','inherit','closed','closed','','ericaindman_wit','','','2015-12-22 10:40:10','2015-12-22 15:40:10','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/EricaIndman_WIT.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(617,4,'2015-12-22 10:39:36','2015-12-22 15:39:36','','DanaPylayeva_WIT','','inherit','closed','closed','','danapylayeva_wit','','','2015-12-22 10:39:57','2015-12-22 15:39:57','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/DanaPylayeva_WIT.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(618,4,'2015-12-22 10:51:55','2015-12-22 15:51:55','','Camille Stewart','','inherit','closed','closed','','camille-stewart','','','2015-12-22 17:16:33','2015-12-22 22:16:33','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Camille-Stewart.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(619,4,'2015-12-22 11:02:44','2015-12-22 16:02:44','','Valerie Woolard','','inherit','closed','closed','','valerie-woolard','','','2015-12-22 15:31:50','2015-12-22 20:31:50','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Valerie-Woolard.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(620,4,'2015-12-22 11:30:43','2015-12-22 16:30:43','','Grace Killelea','','inherit','closed','closed','','grace-killelea-2','','','2015-12-22 11:31:18','2015-12-22 16:31:18','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Grace-Killelea.jpeg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(622,4,'2015-12-22 15:10:48','2015-12-22 20:10:48','Mayra is a brand journalist, senior digital strategist, visual storyteller, social media coach, web show host, speaker, blogger and upcoming author. When not blogging here, Mayra can be found communicating in status updates, thinking in hashtags and living life in 140-characters.','Mayra Ruiz-McPherson','','publish','closed','closed','','mayra-ruiz-mcpherson','','','2016-01-20 15:48:56','2016-01-20 20:48:56','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=622',0,'speaker','',0),(623,4,'2015-12-22 15:15:43','2015-12-22 20:15:43','Paula Darling’s experience spans a career of 25 years in Risk and Asset Management, Portfolio and Collections Management, and the Analytics and Technology areas.  In her role as VP of Acquisitions and Due Diligence at GE Capital, and as Chief Operating officer at EduCap, she was responsible for meeting financial goals, portfolio reporting, analytics, bond reporting, and portfolio performance.  She is a leader in the Business Intelligence community with vast experience building scorecards and employing predictive modeling for producing the strongest and most successful results in financial services, sales, and higher education.   Paula brings all of her skills and strategic acumen acquired from her leadership positions to Mined Systems to produce results for clients through strategy, tactics and predictive analytics.','Paula Darling','','publish','closed','closed','','paula-darling','','','2016-01-31 10:22:33','2016-01-31 15:22:33','',0,'http://womenintechs.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=623',0,'speaker','',0),(624,4,'2015-12-22 15:26:55','2015-12-22 20:26:55','<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;In her 17 years of industry experience Dana has been exposed to different areas of IT as a Java Developer, an Architect, a DBA Manager, a Scrum Master and an Agile Coach. Every role she has had in her career has given her an opportunity to apply her passion for agile principles and practices and to help others recognize benefits of Agile approach to project management.\\nDana holds MS in Robotics and Mechatronics from Moscow State University of Technology \\&quot;STANKIN\\&quot; as well as Certified Scrum Professional (CSP) certification from Scrum Alliance.\\nShe currently works at Rakuten Marketing in New York City and enjoys training and coaching teams, helping them in their continuous improvement as well as facilitating positive changes in organizational culture.\\nActive member of global agile community, she has been volunteering at Agile Alliance conferences for the past 10 years. As a session reviewer and a submission coach, she provides guidance to prospective speakers and contributes to a program selection process at Agile Alliance and Scrum Alliance conferences. A member of \\u201cWomen in Agile\\u201d group and NYC Scrum User group, she leads \\u201cBig Apple Scrum Day 2016\\u201d conference organizing initiative. Dana enjoys speaking, facilitating workshops and training with groups from 10 to 120 people. She spoke at sixteen conferences in seven countries on topics ranging from DevOps to User Story Mapp